  <prompt>
    Build the `update_workspace_tab(tabId, changes, expectedLastUserEditAt?)` chat tool as
    an `IToolHandler`. Per Q8 conflict resolution: USER WINS. On invocation: agent passes
    its observed `expectedLastUserEditAt` (the timestamp it saw when the tab was last
    read into the prompt). Handler fetches current tab via `WorkspaceStateService`; if
    current `lastUserEditAt` is newer than `expectedLastUserEditAt`, REFUSES the write
    with a polite "stale read" response telling the agent to re-read the tab before
    re-attempting. If timestamps match (or `expectedLastUserEditAt` is null indicating
    agent-just-created tab), applies the changes via `UpsertTabAsync`. Emits
    `workspace.tab_edited` event with deterministic IDs (tabId, sessionId, matterId)
    only. ADR-015 binding: NEVER log `changes` body in telemetry â€” only tool name +
    decision (`applied` | `refused_stale_read`) + timestamp. Conflict-detection logic is
    bulletproof â€” race conditions covered in unit tests.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior BFF engineer with concurrency-control expertise + familiarity with optimistic
    concurrency via timestamp comparison.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `update_workspace_tab` tool installed; LLM can update tabs. Stale writes refused
    cleanly with a re-read instruction. Race condition tests pass. Telemetry
    governance-compliant per ADR-015.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="project-spec">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-plan">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/plan.md</file>
